{
  "A foramen is:": "",
  "A depression or cavity in a bone": "",
  "An opening or hole in a bone": "",
  "A bump or raised area on a bone": "",
  "A smooth, flat joint surface": "",
  "A foramen is a natural opening or hole in a bone that typically serves as a passageway for blood vessels, nerves, or other structures. Examples include the foramen magnum and the mental foramen.": "",
  "The glenoid cavity is located on the:": "",
  "Humerus": "",
  "Femur": "",
  "Scapula": "",
  "Hip bone": "",
  "The glenoid cavity (glenoid fossa) is the shallow depression on the lateral angle of the scapula that forms the socket of the shoulder joint, receiving the head of the humerus.": "",
  "The olecranon process is found on the:": "",
  "Radius": "",
  "Ulna": "",
  "The olecranon process is the large, curved projection at the proximal end of the ulna that forms the bony point of the elbow and serves as the attachment point for the triceps brachii muscle.": "",
  "The greater trochanter is located on the:": "",
  "Tibia (lateral condyle near the knee joint)": "",
  "Femur (lateral projection near the hip)": "",
  "Scapula (superior border of the spine)": "",
  "Humerus (proximal lateral epicondyle area)": "",
  "The greater trochanter is a large, bony prominence on the lateral surface of the proximal femur near the hip joint. It serves as an attachment site for several hip muscles and can be palpated at the outer hip.": "",
  "The mastoid process is located on the:": "",
  "Occipital bone": "",
  "Temporal bone (behind the ear)": "",
  "Mandible": "",
  "Frontal bone": "",
  "The mastoid process is a rounded, conical projection of the temporal bone located just behind and below the ear. It serves as an attachment point for several neck muscles including the sternocleidomastoid.": "",
  "The acromion is located on the:": "",
  "Clavicle (the lateral sternal end)": "",
  "Scapula (point of the shoulder)": "",
  "Sternum (the superior manubrium)": "",
  "Humerus (the proximal head region)": "",
  "The acromion is a flat, bony projection extending laterally from the spine of the scapula, forming the highest point of the shoulder. It articulates with the clavicle at the acromioclavicular (AC) joint.": "",
  "The medial malleolus is located on the:": "",
  "Femur (distal medial condyle)": "",
  "Tibia (inner ankle bump)": "",
  "Humerus (medial epicondyle area)": "",
  "Fibula (lateral ankle prominence)": "",
  "The medial malleolus is the bony prominence on the medial (inner) side of the ankle, formed by the distal end of the tibia. It forms the inner wall of the ankle joint (talocrural joint).": "",
  "The xiphoid process is part of the:": "",
  "Sternum (the inferior cartilaginous tip)": "",
  "A cervical vertebra (the spinous process tip)": "",
  "Scapula (the inferior angle projection)": "",
  "Clavicle (the lateral acromial end)": "",
  "The xiphoid process is the small, cartilaginous inferior tip of the sternum. It serves as an attachment point for the diaphragm and some abdominal muscles and is an important landmark for CPR hand placement.": "",
  "Spinous processes are found on:": "",
  "Vertebrae (posterior projections)": "",
  "The ribs (costal tubercle projections)": "",
  "The skull (occipital crest ridges)": "",
  "The femur (linea aspera ridges)": "",
  "Spinous processes are the posterior projections of vertebrae that can be palpated as a series of bumps along the midline of the back. They serve as attachment points for muscles and ligaments of the spine.": "",
  "The zygomatic arch forms the:": "",
  "Jaw": "",
  "Forehead": "",
  "Cheekbone": "",
  "Nose bridge": "",
  "The zygomatic arch (cheekbone) is a bony bridge formed by the zygomatic process of the temporal bone and the temporal process of the zygomatic bone. It creates the prominence of the cheek and serves as an attachment point for the masseter muscle.": "",
  "What is a fossa?": "",
  "A smooth, flat articular surface": "",
  "A sharp, pointed projection on a bone": "",
  "A shallow depression or cavity in or on a bone": "",
  "A hole through which nerves pass": "",
  "A fossa is a shallow depression, groove, or cavity in or on a bone. It often serves as an articular surface or a point where muscles attach. Examples include the glenoid fossa of the scapula and the olecranon fossa of the humerus.": "",
  "What is a condyle?": "",
  "A flat articular surface": "",
  "A sharp, narrow ridge on a bone": "",
  "An opening in a bone for blood vessels": "",
  "A large, rounded projection at the end of a bone that forms part of a joint": "",
  "A condyle is a large, smooth, rounded articular projection at the end of a bone that participates in joint formation. Examples include the medial and lateral condyles of the femur at the knee joint and the occipital condyles of the skull.": "",
  "What is a tuberosity?": "",
  "A smooth, flat articular surface on a bone that provides a low-friction gliding area for joint movement": "",
  "A hole or passageway through a bone that allows nerves and blood vessels to travel to surrounding tissues": "",
  "A large, roughened projection on a bone that serves as a muscle or ligament attachment site": "",
  "A shallow, concave depression on a bone surface that receives the end of another bone to form an articulation": "",
  "A tuberosity is a large, roughened, irregular area on a bone that typically serves as an attachment point for muscles or ligaments. Examples include the tibial tuberosity (where the patellar ligament attaches) and the deltoid tuberosity of the humerus.": "",
  "What is a process in bone anatomy?": "",
  "Any prominent projection or outgrowth from a bone": "",
  "Any depression or cavity in a bone": "",
  "A channel running through the interior of a bone": "",
  "The sequence of steps in bone development": "",
  "In bone anatomy, a process is any prominent projection or outgrowth that extends from the surface of a bone. Processes serve as attachment points for muscles, tendons, and ligaments, or as articulating surfaces. Examples include the spinous process, mastoid process, and olecranon process.": "",
  "What is the mental foramen?": "",
  "A hole in the temporal bone for the ear canal": "",
  "An opening in the maxilla (upper jaw) for blood vessels": "",
  "The opening in the occipital bone for the spinal cord": "",
  "An opening on the mandible (lower jaw) near the chin through which the mental nerve and vessels pass": "",
  "The mental foramen is a small opening on the anterolateral surface of the mandible near the chin. The mental nerve and blood vessels pass through it, supplying sensation to the lower lip and chin area. 'Mental' here derives from the Latin 'mentum' meaning chin.": "",
  "What is the deltoid tuberosity?": "",
  "A roughened area on the lateral midshaft of the humerus where the deltoid muscle attaches": "",
  "A roughened area on the ulna where the deltoid muscle attaches": "",
  "A bony projection on the femur for hip muscle attachment": "",
  "A smooth area on the scapula where the deltoid originates": "",
  "The deltoid tuberosity is a V-shaped roughened area on the lateral surface of the midshaft of the humerus. It serves as the insertion point for the deltoid muscle, which is the primary muscle responsible for arm abduction.": "",
  "What is a trochanter?": "",
  "A hole in a bone for blood vessel passage": "",
  "A large, blunt projection found only on the femur that serves as a muscle attachment site": "",
  "A sharp, narrow ridge along a bone's surface": "",
  "A smooth, rounded articular surface at a joint": "",
  "A trochanter is a very large, blunt, irregular projection found exclusively on the femur. There are two trochanters: the greater trochanter (lateral) and the lesser trochanter (medial), both serving as attachment sites for powerful hip and thigh muscles.": "",
  "What is the obturator foramen?": "",
  "A large opening in the hip bone (os coxae) formed between the ischium and pubis": "",
  "The opening in a vertebra for the spinal cord": "",
  "A foramen in the sacrum for spinal nerves": "",
  "A hole in the skull for the optic nerve": "",
  "The obturator foramen is a large, oval opening in the hip bone, formed by the ischium and pubis. In life, it is nearly completely covered by the obturator membrane, with only a small opening (obturator canal) for the obturator nerve and vessels.": "",
  "What is a facet in bone anatomy?": "",
  "A deep groove in a bone for nerve passage": "",
  "A large projection for muscle attachment": "",
  "A large, roughened area for tendon attachment": "",
  "A small, smooth, flat articular surface on a bone": "",
  "A facet is a small, smooth, flat or slightly curved articular surface on a bone where it meets another bone. Facets are commonly found on vertebrae (superior and inferior articular facets) and on ribs where they articulate with thoracic vertebrae.": "",
  "What is the lateral malleolus?": "",
  "A projection on the calcaneus at the heel": "",
  "A bump on the femur near the knee": "",
  "The bony bump on the inner side of the ankle, formed by the tibia": "",
  "The bony bump on the outer side of the ankle, formed by the distal end of the fibula": "",
  "The lateral malleolus is the bony prominence on the outer (lateral) side of the ankle, formed by the distal end of the fibula. Together with the medial malleolus of the tibia, it forms a mortise that cradles the talus to create the ankle joint.": "",
  "A nursing student is preparing to give an intramuscular injection in the deltoid muscle of the upper arm. She needs to identify the bony landmark on the humerus where the deltoid inserts to avoid injecting too close to bone. Which landmark should she locate?": "",
  "The greater tubercle of the humerus": "",
  "The deltoid tuberosity": "",
  "The olecranon process": "",
  "The medial epicondyle": "",
  "The deltoid tuberosity is the roughened area on the lateral midshaft of the humerus where the deltoid muscle inserts. Nurses use this landmark to properly position intramuscular injections in the deltoid, ensuring the needle enters the muscle belly and not the bone.": "",
  "A dentist is about to administer a local anesthetic to numb the lower lip and chin area for a dental procedure. She needs to locate a specific opening on the mandible to target the nerve exiting there. Which landmark should she find?": "",
  "The infraorbital foramen below the eye": "",
  "The mandibular foramen on the inner surface of the mandible": "",
  "The mental foramen on the outer surface of the mandible near the chin": "",
  "The foramen magnum at the base of the skull": "",
  "The mental foramen is located on the anterolateral surface of the mandible, typically below the premolar teeth. The mental nerve exits here, supplying sensation to the lower lip and chin. Dentists target this foramen for a mental nerve block to anesthetize this area.": "",
  "A patient presents after a fall with shoulder pain. The physician palpates a bony prominence at the tip of the shoulder and notes tenderness at the joint between this structure and the clavicle. Which two bony landmarks form this joint?": "",
  "The acromion of the scapula and the lateral end of the clavicle": "",
  "The manubrium and the first rib": "",
  "The glenoid cavity and the humeral head": "",
  "The coracoid process and the clavicle": "",
  "The acromioclavicular (AC) joint is formed by the acromion of the scapula and the lateral end of the clavicle at the top of the shoulder. AC joint injuries are common from falls onto the shoulder and are often called 'separated shoulders.'": "",
  "An orthopedic surgeon is planning surgery for a hip fracture. She examines the X-ray and notes a fracture at the large, lateral bony projection near the top of the femur. Which bony landmark is fractured?": "",
  "The femoral neck": "",
  "The femoral head": "",
  "The lateral condyle of the femur": "",
  "The greater trochanter": "",
  "The greater trochanter is the large, lateral bony prominence at the proximal femur, palpable at the outer hip. Greater trochanter fractures are common in elderly patients who fall directly onto the hip. This landmark serves as an attachment for gluteal and hip rotator muscles.": "",
  "A physical therapist is evaluating a patient with neck pain. She palpates a bony bump behind the patient's ear and notes tenderness. Which bone landmark is she palpating, and which bone is it part of?": "",
  "The mastoid process of the temporal bone": "",
  "The styloid process of the temporal bone": "",
  "The external occipital protuberance of the occipital bone": "",
  "The zygomatic process of the temporal bone": "",
  "The mastoid process is a conical bony prominence of the temporal bone located just behind and below the ear. It is easily palpable and serves as an attachment point for the sternocleidomastoid and other neck muscles. Tenderness here can indicate mastoiditis or neck muscle strain.": "",
  "During a sports physical, a physician asks a teenage athlete to extend her leg and then palpates a bump just below the kneecap on the front of the shin. The athlete reports tenderness there. Which bony landmark is tender, and what condition might this suggest?": "",
  "The tibial tuberosity; tenderness here in an adolescent may suggest Osgood-Schlatter disease": "",
  "The head of the fibula; this suggests a peroneal nerve injury": "",
  "The medial condyle of the tibia; this suggests a knee sprain": "",
  "The lateral malleolus; this suggests an ankle sprain": "",
  "The tibial tuberosity is the bony bump on the anterior proximal tibia where the patellar ligament attaches. In growing adolescents, repetitive stress from sports can cause inflammation at this site, a condition called Osgood-Schlatter disease.": "",
  "A medical student is examining a skull and locates a butterfly-shaped bone that spans the width of the cranial floor and contains a saddle-shaped depression that houses the pituitary gland. Which bone and which specific landmark has she identified?": "",
  "The frontal bone and the supraorbital foramen": "",
  "The sphenoid bone and the sella turcica": "",
  "The occipital bone and the foramen magnum": "",
  "The ethmoid bone and its cribriform plate": "",
  "The sphenoid bone is a butterfly-shaped bone in the cranial floor. The sella turcica ('Turkish saddle') is a saddle-shaped depression on the superior surface of the sphenoid body that houses and protects the pituitary gland.": "",
  "An emergency physician is evaluating a patient who sprained her ankle. To determine if a fracture is present, he palpates the bony bumps on both sides of the ankle. He notes tenderness on the outer ankle bump. Which specific bony landmark is tender, and which bone does it belong to?": "",
  "The medial malleolus of the tibia": "",
  "The lateral malleolus of the fibula": "",
  "The talus": "",
  "The calcaneus": "",
  "The lateral malleolus is the bony prominence on the outer side of the ankle, formed by the distal end of the fibula. Tenderness at this landmark after an ankle injury raises suspicion for a fibular (lateral malleolus) fracture, which is the most common type of ankle fracture.": "",
  "A patient is scheduled for a lumbar puncture (spinal tap). The physician uses the spinous processes of the vertebrae as landmarks to determine the correct insertion point. She palpates the bumps along the patient's midline lower back. What are these bumps, and why are they useful landmarks?": "",
  "Spinous processes; they are the most superficial vertebral structures and indicate the vertebral level for needle insertion between vertebrae": "",
  "Laminae; they protect the spinal cord during the procedure": "",
  "Transverse processes; they mark the lateral boundaries of the spinal canal": "",
  "Vertebral bodies; they can be felt through the back muscles": "",
  "Spinous processes are the posterior projections of vertebrae that can be palpated along the midline of the back. They serve as essential surface landmarks for clinical procedures like lumbar punctures, allowing the physician to identify the correct vertebral level for needle insertion.": "",
  "A forensic anthropologist is examining a pelvis and notices a large oval opening bordered by the ischium and pubis that is mostly covered by a membrane in living individuals. She also notes the smooth, cup-shaped depression where the three hip bones fused. What are these two landmarks?": "",
  "The sacral hiatus and the sacroiliac joint": "",
  "The obturator foramen and the acetabulum": "",
  "The pubic symphysis and the ischial tuberosity": "",
  "The greater sciatic notch and the iliac fossa": "",
  "The obturator foramen is the large oval opening in the hip bone bordered by the ischium and pubis (covered by the obturator membrane in life). The acetabulum is the deep, cup-shaped socket where the ilium, ischium, and pubis fuse and where the femoral head articulates to form the hip joint.": ""
}